  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Defining App Requirements**\n\nOkay, I\'m now delving into the core needs of the application. I\'ve pinpointed the user\'s primary goal: an MVP e-commerce site for Algerian traditional crafts and clothing. This means focusing on core e-commerce functionality, and starting with a focus on \"Arts and clothing\" as a first category. I\'ll need to define the fundamental building blocks of this category to keep it simple.\n\n\n**Clarifying Scope & Modalities**\n\nI\'m now clarifying the scope \342\200\223 distinguishing between items for rent versus purchase. Sellers need a clear dashboard for inventory and fulfillment. I\342\200\231m thinking a React prototype for UI/UX is essential for modeling. The design needs to resonate with Algerian culture: clay tones, emerald greens, and Zellij accents are key. I\'m focusing on a single-view layout, but am pausing on navigation based on request guidelines.\n\n\n**Refining Application Architecture**\n\nI\'m now implementing the sub-views: Checkout, Seller Dashboard, and a Catalog with Buy/Rent filters. I\'m leaning toward a polished single-page application with a header tab system or a simple mode switch between \"Shop\" and \"Seller Portal.\" The primary focus will be on the core data structures, type definitions, and views, keeping a highly modular architecture in mind as per directives.\n\n\n**Defining Data Structures**\n\nI\'m now focusing on implementing the core data structures and types. I\'m creating `/src/types.ts` to define `Product` and `Order` types.  `Product` will include essential fields like `id`, `name`, `category`, and `price`. I\'m also including `rentPrice` if the item is rentable, and attributes for origin and stock. I\'ll define `Order` with `id` and `buyerName`. I\'m also preparing to update `metadata.json` with a descriptive application name, such as \"Dzair Craft - Algerian Traditional Marketplace\" to conform with requirements.\n\n\n**Elaborating Order Details**\n\nI\'m now expanding the data structure. I\'m finalizing the `Order` type, including fields like `buyerEmail` and an array of `CartItem` objects, each detailing a product and quantity. I\'m also including purchase type, `totalAmount`, `status`, `date`, `paymentMethod`, and rental-specific details. Additionally, I\'m creating the `CartItem` type as a dedicated structure. I plan to use this to build out real data in `/src/data.ts` next.\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "I will begin by preparing our application\'s metadata, giving it the literal name **Dzair Craft** and a culturally descriptive explanation suitable for stakeholders."
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 8
      nanos: 537976767
    }
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
  }
}
